    "creation_date" : 1242368018,
    "answer_id" : 867206,
    "question_id" : 867194,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>That's correct, initially the <code>ResultSet</code>'s cursor is pointing to before the first row, if the first call to <code>next()</code> returns <code>false</code> then there was no data in the <code>ResultSet</code>.</p>\n\n<p>If you use this method, you may have to call <code>beforeFirst()</code> immediately after to reset it, since it has positioned itself past the first row now.</p>\n\n<p>It should be noted however, that <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/6813771/1030\">Seifer's answer</a> below is a more elegant solution to this question. </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 12262,
      "reputation" : 104314,
      "user_id" : 24054,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/24059909b82438e84ac480148dbdc4d6?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "kgiannakakis",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/24054/kgiannakakis"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 21,
    "last_activity_date" : 1242368172,
    "creation_date" : 1242368172,
    "answer_id" : 867210,
    "question_id" : 867194,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>You would usually do something like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>while ( resultSet.next() ) { \n   // Read the next item\n   resultSet.getString(\"columnName\");\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>If you want to report an empty set, add a variable counting the items read. If you only need to read a single item, then your code is adequate.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 31309,
      "reputation" : 3448,
      "user_id" : 85868,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 89,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a3883ced75dbc92d6622b016ea6a6ef8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Nuoji",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/85868/nuoji"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1242368421,
    "creation_date" : 1242368421,
    "answer_id" : 867232,
    "question_id" : 867194,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>That would work if you want to see if there are any rows in the result set yes. </p>\n\n<p>Note that <code>next()</code> always moves to the next row, so if you are planning on doing any reading from the result set you need to take that into account.</p>\n\n<p>Usual usage with ResultSet (when simply reading) is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>while (resultSet.next())\n{\n   ... read from the row here ...\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Which obviously won't work correctly if you invoked <code>next()</code> once already to check if the result set was empty, so watch out for that. Although there are methods for \"backing up\", they are not supported for all types of result sets.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 23183,
      "reputation" : 18846,
      "user_id" : 57883,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 69,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9f4a12b955cb61fcf67b031040f7da51?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Maslow",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/57883/maslow"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 58,
    "last_activity_date" : 1243721968,
    "creation_date" : 1243721968,
    "answer_id" : 930757,
    "question_id" : 867194,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>you could always do the next up front, and just do a post loop check</p>\n\n<pre><code>if (!resultSet.next() ) {\n    System.out.println(\"no data\");\n} else {\n\n    do {\n     //statement(s)\n    } while (resultSet.next());\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
