      "creation_date" : 1723537562,
      "post_id" : 28561992,
      "comment_id" : 139046372,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "from the same link to <code>first()</code> posted in the answer: &quot;<b>Throws:</b> <code>SQLException</code> - if ... or the result set type is <code>TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY</code> - so worse then  <code>isBeforeFirst()</code> - it definitively does no work for forward-only result sets (while optionally for <code>isBeforeFirst()</code>) -- and  moving the cursor with <code>first()</code>, to test if there is data, is more overkill than just checking <code>isBeforeFirst()</code>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3062937,
      "reputation" : 3794,
      "user_id" : 2641361,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 83,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/wfaNz.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "OddDev",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2641361/odddev"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 9,
    "last_activity_date" : 1425380765,
    "last_edit_date" : 1425380765,
    "creation_date" : 1424177592,
    "answer_id" : 28561992,
    "question_id" : 867194,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>According to the most viable answer the suggestion is to use \"isBeforeFirst()\". <strong>That's not the best solution if you don't have a \"forward only type\"</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>There's a method called \"<a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/sql/ResultSet.html#first()\" rel=\"noreferrer\">.first()</a>\". It's less overkill to get the exact same result. You check whether there is something in your \"resultset\" and don't advance your cursor. </p>\n\n<p>The documentation states: \"(...) false if there are <strong>no rows in the result set</strong>\".</p>\n\n<pre><code>if(rs.first()){\n    //do stuff      \n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>You can also just call isBeforeFirst() to test if there are any rows returned without advancing the cursor, then proceed normally. –  SnakeDoc Sep 2 '14 at 19:00 </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>However, there's a difference between \"isBeforeFirst()\" and \"first()\". First generates an exception if done on a resultset from type \"forward only\". </p>\n\n<p>Compare the two throw sections: \n<a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/sql/ResultSet.html#isBeforeFirst()\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/sql/ResultSet.html#isBeforeFirst()</a>\n<a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/sql/ResultSet.html#first()\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/sql/ResultSet.html#first()</a></p>\n\n<p>Okay, basically this means that you should use \"isBeforeFirst\" as long as you have a \"forward only\" type. Otherwise it's less overkill to use \"first()\". </p>\n"
  }, {
